entry.title: Add unit-tests for closing quic session and posting migration right after
entry.content:
* Connection Migration has a different operation mode when closing

connection unlike the usual. It depends on `closeSessionOnErrorLater` which

will close the session(but not call the destructor) then post a task to destroy

the session. This has introduced race conditions and plenty of bugs for Cronet / Clank.



* This CL just adds unit-tests which exhibits the same behavior by calling `closeSessionOnErrorLater`

explicitly then calling `migrateToSocket` which replicates the latest crash that happened on Cronet.



* Added another unit-test that replicates the crash but from a different position where `FinishMigrate` is called

just after `closeSessionOnErrorLater`.



* This is just another patch for the `closeSessionOnErrorLater` disaster, I will follow-up with some CLs

to migrate to closeSessionOnError.



* In an Ideal world, we should not be using CloseSessionOnErrorLater as it

introduces a window for race conditions to happen. We should be using

CloseSessionOnError as this will guarantee that no other callback can be

executed after the session has been closed.

entry.title: media/gpu/test: Fix H.264 NALU boundary detection
entry.content:
video_decode_accelerator_(perf_)test's EncodedDataHelper is used for

reading H.264 (and other codecs ofc) bitstreams frames from disk. To

find the NALU boundary, it looks for the marker 0x00 00 00 01; however,

NALUs can also be marked by 0x00 00 01 (*); this CL fixes this.



This situation was found during V4L2StatefulVideoDecoder bringup: it

was observed that said decoder was fed very large media::DecoderBuffers

for some H.264 specific "main" test vectors (e.g. CAPCM1_Sand_E.h264)

and this was traced down to EncodedDataHelper not reading one NALU at

a time from disk, but bundling very many at once.



With this CL, all H.264 main test vectors verify MD5Sums on trogdor

_except_ for CVPCMNL2_SVA_C.h264 (argh! :).



(*) This is described in the spec but a quick search gives as well e.g.

https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/directshow/h-264-video-types#h264-bitstream-with-start-codes

entry.title: Remove Form Card Matching In Mandatory Reauth Opt-In Flow (CL 1 of 3)
entry.content:
The old behavior here was that if the user autofilled a card via non-

interactive authentication (green path), and then deleted the card in

the form and manually typed in a different card, we would do a matching

check to make sure that the card in the form matched the most recently

filled card before we offer re-auth opt-in.



With this CL, we will remove the matching check. Instead, with this CL,

we will offer re-auth opt-in if the user's most recent autofill moment

was a non-interactive authentication (green path).



The difference in functionality with this CL will be that in the case

where a user green paths a card, then deletes the card and manually

types in a different card in the form, we will now offer re-auth opt-in.

Before this CL, in this scenario, we would not offer re-auth opt-in.



After discussing this case within engineering and with product, we

realized that it is an extremely rare edge cased based on the UMA data.

Handling it adds a lot of complexity in the code, and not offering re-

auth opt-in might actually not be the ideal user journey from a product

perspective. It is possible if a user went through non-interactive

authentication but then manually typed in a different card, they

actually disliked the non-interactive authentication and wanted to use a

different card. Offering to always authenticate can actually make a lot

of sense in this use-case.



CL #2 in this chain will update the associated histograms and enums to

match this refactor.



CL #3 in this chain will move the class variable that denotes the most

recent payments autofill was a non-interactive authentication into

CreditCardAccessManager.

entry.title: [Extensions] Don't track extra header counts in the RulesMonitorService.
entry.content:
The RulesMonitorService currently increments or decrements a counter

in the ExtensionWebRequestEventRouter, depending on the presence of a

matcher that matches extra headers the current rule set. This isn't

necessary and creates a cyclic dependency between the two instances.



This currently isn't an issue because the

ExtensionWebRequestEventRouter instance is singleton, but it will be

one once we move to per-BrowserContext instances. Also, the current

implementation involves additional code in the RuleMonitorService to

handle the count.



This CL breaks this dependency by exposing a boolean accessor function

that the ExtensionWebRequestEventRouter can use to determine if there

are any such matchers.

entry.title: Reland "[wpt-metadata] Refine updates for `chrome` and `debug`"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 0f05c7e5dad22d2c2d0454bde0bcc030cf25e1cf



Changes since original:

`manifestupdate` also evaluates existing `expected`, so the old

property filtering was too aggressive. Relax this by only filtering

to all usable properties, and only filter to update properties when

deciding what results to fill in. This implements a kind of

expectation inheritance, which will be useful for `--reset-results`

(crbug.com/1480061).



Original change's description:

> [wpt-metadata] Refine updates for `chrome` and `debug`

> * Do not generate any `chrome` configurations with nonempty

> `virtual_suite`, as `chrome` will not run virtual tests.

> * Remove `debug` as an update property when no debug builders are

> present, as debug builders are usually CI-only and therefore can't be

> used to set expectations against a CL. In that case, automatically

> extend the release results to the debug counterpart, which are usually

> identical. This mimics how the WPT importer doesn't add

> TestExpectations with a `Debug` specifier.

> * Remove the implicit unused `subsuite` property [1], which interferes

> with updates.

entry.title: media/gpu/v4l2:V4L2StatefulVD: support H.264 fragment reassembly
entry.content:
H.264 bitstreams can have fragments of full "frames". Evidence and

legacy code points to stateful drivers (at least QC venus) needing

full frames to be enqueued at once. H.264 spec also speaks about that.



This CL teaches the code to use a new H264FrameReassembler class to figure out frame boundaries and to reassemble (concatenate) bunches

of DecoderBuffers into enqueue-able ones. This new class needs to be

plugged in during normal Decode() and also End-of-Stream Decode()

calls, otherwise much of the code remains untouched and this CL is

a massive code addition.



With this, all of the "first_mb_in_slice" test vectors start passing

(e.g. baseline/BA1_FT_C.h264, BASQP1_Sony_C.h264) and also all the

currently failing H264 baseline (but this might be a fluke).

entry.title: Major overhaul of ExceptionState in the v8 bindings
entry.content:
* Currently, interface.py has a mechanism for calculating the

appropriate ExceptionContext::Context type, but named and indexed

interceptors generally have hard-coded values. Plumb the

information required to use the general mechanism.

* Rename a bunch of ExecutionContext::Context types, so that it's

easier to generate the correct type in the bindings and we use

more consistent names throughout.

* As part of updating the named and indexed interceptors to use the

general ExceptionState construction mechanism, remove the large

blocks of code pasted into those interceptors and break them up

in to a proper tree of code nodes in the bindings generator.

* Named and indexed interceptors are different from most other

bindings in that the relevant property name is dynamically

provided by script, rather than being a string literal known by

the bindings generator. This requires that ExceptionContext be

able to handle property names that are not string literals. This

is accomplished by having ExceptionContext have the option of

holding a WTF::String that backs the property name, in order to

ensure the c-string property name is kept alive for the entire

lifetime of the ExceptionContext.

* The consumers of the ExceptionContext::property_name_ will

eventually want the property name as a WTF::String, so change

ExceptionContext::GetPropertyName() to return a WTF::String. This

will either return the interceptor property name string directly,

or wrap a string literal in a String before returning it.

* We now plumb enough information to actually report the property

name in exception for named and indexed interceptors. Update the

error messages and associated test expectations.

entry.title: Consider nested snap areas on layout snaps
entry.content:
When snapping after a layout change, we snap to the

scroll-snap-align-specified position. This may cause unwanted jumps

in the case of large snap areas, e.g. when android shows browser

controls.

For large snap areas (areas larger than the snapport) we should,

instead, consider snapping to the closest covering position.

This is the behavior for snaps that occur at the end of a scroll.

This patch makes snaps after layout changes conform to this behavior.



Large snap areas may contain nested snap areas which may themselves be large snap areas that contain nested snap areas, so this patch

accounts for this by looking at all snap areas that overlap with the

snap area we are attempting to snap to.



A few notes about the test changes:



snap-area-overflow-boundary.html & changing-scroll-snap-align.html:

the first test cases now takes into account that the relayout

doesn't reset the scroll position.

A test case is also added for changing-scroll-snap-align.html verifying the behavior of small snap targets.
